# Are Abortions Harmful to Women? A Comprehensive Review

Abortion remains one of the most debated medical and social issues worldwide. Central to this debate is the question: Are abortions harmful to women? This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of the physical and mental health consequences of abortion, drawing on a wide range of scientific literature, systematic reviews, cohort studies, and meta-analyses published primarily since 2000. The goal is to present an objective, comprehensive, and nuanced understanding of the potential harms and risks associated with abortion, emphasizing the quality and reliability of the evidence.

---

## Physical Health Consequences of Abortion

### Safety Compared to Childbirth

Legal induced abortion, when performed under appropriate medical conditions, is generally considered safe and is associated with lower immediate morbidity and mortality compared to childbirth. For instance, Raymond and Grimes (2012) analyzed mortality rates in the United States from 1998 to 2005 and found that abortion had a significantly lower mortality rate than childbirth ([Raymond & Grimes, 2012](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22270271/)).

Similarly, the Turnaway Study, a large prospective cohort study, reported that women who gave birth experienced more potentially life-threatening complications such as eclampsia and postpartum hemorrhage than those who had abortions. Moreover, women who gave birth reported a longer need to limit physical activity post-delivery compared to women who had abortions ([Foster et al., 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26576470/)).

| Outcome                          | Abortion Group          | Childbirth Group        |
|---------------------------------|------------------------|------------------------|
| Maternal Deaths                 | Lower                  | Higher                 |
| Life-threatening Complications  | Rare                   | More common (e.g., eclampsia, hemorrhage) |
| Physical Activity Limitation    | Shorter duration        | Longer duration        |

### Long-Term Physical Health Effects

Research on long-term physical consequences such as secondary infertility, ectopic pregnancy, miscarriage, stillbirth, and breast cancer risk has produced mixed findings. The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (NASEM) committee reviewed the epidemiological evidence and concluded that abortion does **not** increase the risk of secondary infertility, pregnancy-related hypertensive disorders, abnormal placentation (after dilation and evacuation), preterm birth (except in cases of multiple prior abortions), breast cancer, or mental health disorders ([NASEM, 2018](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507237/)).

However, an increased risk of very preterm birth (<28 weeks gestation) was associated with having two or more prior aspiration abortions, especially when conception occurs less than six months after abortion ([NASEM, 2018](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507237/)).

### Unsafe Abortions and Complications

Unsafe abortions, defined as those performed by untrained individuals or outside medical guidelines, are a significant source of morbidity and mortality globally. They can cause uterine perforation, incomplete abortion, pelvic infection, and even death. The World Health Organization estimates that unsafe abortions cause approximately 68,000 deaths annually worldwide ([WomenHealthZone](https://www.womenhealthzone.com/womens-reproductive-health/abortion/consequences-of-abortion/)).

### Summary of Physical Health Risks

- **Legal, medically supervised abortions**: Generally safe with lower immediate risks than childbirth.
- **Multiple prior abortions**: Possible increased risk of very preterm birth.
- **Unsafe abortions**: High risk of severe complications and death.
- **Long-term physical risks**: No consistent evidence linking abortion to breast cancer or infertility.

