## Mental Health Consequences of Abortion

### Overview of Research and Methodological Considerations

The mental health impact of abortion has been extensively studied, with over 30 systematic reviews, cohort studies, and analyses of registry data conducted since 1995. However, the literature is complicated by methodological challenges such as recall bias, inadequate control for confounders (especially prior mental health status), and inappropriate comparison groups ([NASEM, 2018](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507237/)).

The most rigorous studies use documented medical records, control for pre-existing mental health conditions, and compare women who had abortions to those who delivered unwanted pregnancies.

### Mental Health Outcomes Compared to Childbirth

A systematic review by Charles et al. (2008) and a quantitative synthesis by Coleman (2011) found that women who had abortions had an increased risk of mental health problems compared to women who delivered, including depression, anxiety, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and substance abuse disorders ([Charles et al., 2008](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507237/); [Coleman, 2011](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507237/)).

A detailed analysis of 30 studies showed:

| Comparison Group                 | Number of Studies | Findings of Increased Risk in Abortion Group | Findings of No Difference | Findings of Worse Outcome in Childbirth Group |
|--------------------------------|-------------------|----------------------------------------------|---------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| Abortion vs. Childbirth         | 19                | 13                                           | 5                         | 1                                             |
| Abortion vs. Unplanned Childbirth | 7                 | 4                                            | 3                         | 0                                             |
| Abortion vs. Miscarriage       | 9                 | 3                                            | 4                         | 2 (short-term anxiety/depression higher in miscarriage; long-term higher in abortion) |

This suggests a consistent pattern where abortion is associated with a higher risk of mental health problems compared to childbirth, even when controlling for the unintended nature of the pregnancy ([LiveAction, 2019](https://www.liveaction.org/news/psychological-consequences-abortion/)).

### Suicide and Suicidal Behaviors

Several studies report elevated suicide rates among women who have had abortions compared to those who delivered:

- Scandinavian women had a suicide rate nearly six times greater within 12 months post-abortion compared to post-childbirth (34.9 vs. 5.9 per 1000) ([Gissler et al., 1996](https://www.deveber.org/womens-health-after-abortion/)).
- Studies in Wales and the U.S. found suicide rates 3.25 and 2.6 times higher, respectively, among women who aborted ([Morgan et al., 1987](https://www.deveber.org/womens-health-after-abortion/); [Reardon et al., 2001](https://www.deveber.org/womens-health-after-abortion/)).

### Psychological Effects in Women Without Prior Psychiatric History

Earlier research emphasized that women with prior mental health problems were at greater risk of psychological harm post-abortion. However, more recent, methodologically robust longitudinal studies, including a landmark New Zealand study, demonstrate that even women without previous psychiatric conditions face increased risks of depression and other psychiatric disorders after abortion ([CMF, 2006](https://www.cmf.org.uk/resources/publications/content/?context=article&id=1850)).

### Contrasting Views and Limitations

Some reviews, such as Bradshaw (2003), concluded no long-term mental health differences between abortion and childbirth groups. However, these reviews often excluded more recent studies or failed to control adequately for confounders.

The NASEM committee emphasized that many studies suffer from selective recall bias and inadequate controls, limiting the reliability of some findings. Nevertheless, the preponderance of higher-quality evidence indicates an increased risk of mental health problems post-abortion ([NASEM, 2018](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507237/)).

